---

Proposal: Enhancing SAR Coverage through Targeted Tactical Machine Learning

Objective

To increase detection of suspicious activity in low-volume but high-impact risk scenarios‚Äîsuch as human trafficking and terrorist financing‚Äîby leveraging high-scoring known SARs as ‚Äúbeacons‚Äù to identify similar unalerted customers in the feature space of the tactical machine learning model.

Strategic Rationale

The current model strategy focuses primarily on customers with scores above a high threshold (e.g., 0.98). This maximizes precision but may overlook relevant suspicious activity, especially in niche typologies where the number of SARs is inherently low. By introducing a targeted neighbour-based search around known SARs, the institution can proactively identify hidden suspicious activity that traditional thresholding may miss.

This approach enables:

Improved SAR coverage in under-represented risk categories.

Better alignment between model outputs and intelligence-driven priorities.

Faster feedback loops to refine scenarios and calibrate future models.



---

Proposed Approach

1. Anchor on Known High-Scoring SARs

Select a curated set of confirmed SARs with high model scores (e.g., ‚â•0.98) from priority risk categories such as:

Human trafficking

Terrorist financing

Other strategic typologies identified by Financial Crime Intelligence.


Ensure the selection covers representative patterns of activity within each typology.


2. Neighbourhood Search in Feature Space

Use a similarity search (e.g., k-nearest neighbours in model feature hyperspace) to identify customers with transaction profiles most similar to the anchor SARs.

Focus on unalerted customers with model scores slightly below the existing operational threshold (e.g., 0.85‚Äì0.98).

Prioritize those with tight proximity (high similarity) to anchor SARs.


3. Profiling & Prioritisation Layer

Overlay similarity results with risk scenario metadata (e.g., typology indicators, geography, customer segment).

Rank customers by a combined risk index (e.g., similarity score √ó model score √ó typology weight).

Apply business rules to filter out known low-risk patterns or operational exclusions.


4. Operational Deployment

Generate daily or weekly tactical lists of top-ranked unalerted customers per risk category.

Route these cases to specialist intelligence or investigation teams for rapid triage.

Optionally integrate into existing triage platforms or SAR decisioning workflows.


5. Feedback & Continuous Improvement

Track the outcome of triaged cases (SAR filed, NSTR, false positive).

Refine similarity thresholds and weights to improve hit rates over time.

Identify patterns that can be incorporated into future model training or scenario rules.



---

Expected Benefits

Dimension	Current State	Proposed Enhancement

SAR Coverage	Limited to top threshold alerts	Broader coverage in niche typologies through targeted similarity search
Risk Typology Sensitivity	Strong for high-volume typologies only	Increased sensitivity for human trafficking, terrorist financing, and other low-volume scenarios
Efficiency of Investigations	High precision but may miss high-risk customers	Balanced precision‚Äìrecall trade-off with tactical lists curated for impact
Intelligence Integration	Passive thresholding	Proactive intelligence-driven targeting around known SAR ‚Äúbeacons‚Äù
Model Feedback Loop	Limited feedback to model refinement	Continuous improvement informed by real investigation outcomes



---

Implementation Roadmap

1. Pilot Design (Weeks 1‚Äì4)

Define risk categories, SAR selection criteria, and similarity methodology.

Build proof-of-concept for neighbourhood search and tactical list generation.



2. Operational Pilot (Weeks 5‚Äì10)

Generate weekly tactical lists.

Partner with Financial Crime Intelligence to triage cases and document outcomes.



3. Evaluation & Scaling (Weeks 11‚Äì14)

Assess hit rate, SAR uplift, and operational effort.

Calibrate thresholds and risk weights.

Prepare for scaled deployment.





---

Success Metrics

SAR uplift in low-volume risk categories (e.g., % increase in terrorist financing SARs).

Precision of tactical lists (e.g., proportion of triaged cases leading to SAR filings).

Coverage gap reduction, measured as previously unalerted customers identified.

Investigator feedback on case quality and investigative value.



---

Conclusion

This tactical ML approach enables smarter use of existing model outputs to uncover activity that may otherwise remain invisible. It strengthens coverage of critical but low-prevalence risk scenarios and aligns detection capabilities with the organisation‚Äôs financial crime priorities.

Next step: Approve a 3-month pilot to test and operationalise the neighbour-based tactical model.


